PREDECESSOR OF A NODE IN A BINARY SEARCH TREE (BST)

You are given a Binary Search Tree (BST) and a node value X. Your task is to find the inorder predecessor of node X.

The inorder predecessor of a node is the node that appears just before it in the inorder traversal of the BST.

If no predecessor exists, return -1.

INPUT FORMAT

The first line contains two integers N and X
N is the number of nodes in the BST
X is the node whose predecessor is to be found

The next (N - 1) lines describe the edges of the tree
Each line contains three values:
pi ci Ri

where
pi is the parent node value
ci is the child node value
Ri represents the relationship
L means ci is the left child of pi
R means ci is the right child of pi

OUTPUT FORMAT

Print a single integer
The inorder predecessor of node X if it exists
Otherwise, print -1

CONSTRAINTS

1 ≤ N ≤ 10000
1 ≤ pi, ci ≤ 100000
Ri is either L or R
All node values are distinct
1 ≤ X ≤ 100000

SAMPLE INPUT

7 6
4 2 L
4 6 R
2 3 R
2 1 L
6 5 L
6 7 R

SAMPLE OUTPUT

5

EXPLANATION

In the inorder traversal, node 5 comes just before node 6, so 5 is the predecessor.

